The cardinals gathered in the secure Domus Sanctae Marthae, a hotel built by John Paul II for their comfort during the conclave.
The process could be swift, with a new pope chosen as early as Monday.
Cardinal Ratzinger, a frontrunner, led the procession to the chapel.
The solemn oath of secrecy was taken before the voting began.
Despite hopes for a quick decision, the first ballots failed to elect a new pope.
Speculation surrounds the possibility of a Latin American pope.
The diverse opinions among the cardinals make the outcome uncertain.
The conclave remains a challenging and pivotal event.
